\f0\fs24 \cf0 [\
  \{\
    "slug": "way-maker",\
    "title": "Way Maker",\
    "primary_artist": "Leeland",\
    "default_male_key": "D",\
    "default_female_key": "F",\
    "tempo_bpm": 68,\
    "time_signature": "4/4",\
    "themes": ["miracles", "faith", "presence", "comfort"],\
    "scripture_refs": ["Isaiah 43:16-19", "Psalm 77:13-15", "John 14:6"],\
    "summary_theology": "This song centers on God as the One who makes a way where there is none, who works miracles and keeps His promises even when we cannot see it. It emphasizes the nearness of God in the middle of pain and uncertainty and holds together both transcendence and intimacy. The focus stays on the character of God rather than on our strength or performance which helps anchor a congregation in trust rather than in feelings.",\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This works well in moments where your church needs encouragement in a hard season or when you are calling people to trust God beyond what they see. It can serve as a strong response to a sermon on faith, healing, or perseverance and can also be a powerful closer when you want the room to linger in prayer. Be mindful to keep the focus on God rather than turning it into a song about how intensely we respond so that people rest in who He is rather than how hard they try.",\
    "arrangement_tips": "Start more subdued with simple keys or guitar and gradually build the layers so the band follows the lyrical arc from quiet trust to confident declaration. Keep the tempo steady and avoid letting the dynamics become a wall of sound so there is still room for voices to carry. Leave space between sections for spontaneous prayer or brief scripture readings that reinforce the theme of God making a way.",\
    "tags": ["modern", "ccli_top", "miracle", "faith", "encouragement"]\
  \},\
  \{\
    "slug": "build-my-life",\
    "title": "Build My Life",\
    "primary_artist": "Pat Barrett",\
    "default_male_key": "D",\
    "default_female_key": "F",\
    "tempo_bpm": 72,\
    "time_signature": "4/4",\
    "themes": ["lordship", "holiness", "surrender", "discipleship"],\
    "scripture_refs": ["Matthew 7:24-27", "Romans 12:1-2", "Colossians 1:15-20"],\
    "summary_theology": "This song is a confession that Jesus is the firm foundation and that His worthiness shapes how we live and love others. It draws language from the holiness and supremacy of Christ and moves toward a response of trust and obedience. The theology points worshipers away from building life on emotions or circumstances and toward a life shaped by the character and teaching of Jesus.",\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "Use this when you are calling your church into deeper discipleship, obedience, and everyday worship beyond the service. It can follow a message about foundations, priorities, or holiness and helps people respond in a posture of surrender. Invite people to think about actual areas of life where they need to trust God more so the song becomes an honest response instead of a vague ideal.",\
    "arrangement_tips": "Keep the verses clear and not overly busy so the church can grab hold of the declarations in the chorus. A gentle build into the bridge can make the repetitive lines feel like a prayer that sinks in rather than a shout. Consider a shorter tag at the end and resist over extending the build so the focus stays on reflection and response.",\
    "tags": ["modern", "foundation", "discipleship", "response_song"]\
  \},\
  \{\
    "slug": "graves-into-gardens",\
    "title": "Graves Into Gardens",\
    "primary_artist": "Elevation Worship",\
    "default_male_key": "B",\
    "default_female_key": "D",\
    "tempo_bpm": 72,\
    "time_signature": "6/8",\
    "themes": ["resurrection", "new-life", "hope", "power-of-god"],\
    "scripture_refs": ["Ezekiel 37:1-10", "Isaiah 61:1-3", "Ephesians 2:1-6"],\
    "summary_theology": "This song celebrates the transforming power of God who brings life out of death and beauty out of brokenness. It holds up the contrast between what the world offers and what God alone can do in raising dead hearts and situations. The language leans into resurrection imagery and invites people to trust that God can redeem even the most hopeless places.",\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This fits well on Easter, baptism Sundays, or any time you want to highlight testimonies of transformation. It can follow stories of addiction, loss, or disappointment that God is redeeming and gives people a concrete way to respond in faith. Help your church connect the big language of the song with very real areas where they need God to bring renewal.",\
    "arrangement_tips": "Lean into the groove and let the band lock together rhythmically so the congregation feels the lift without getting lost. The bridge can be a strong moment but it helps to keep the tempo grounded so it does not become rushed shouting. Use dynamics so that when the song peaks it feels earned by the story you have been telling musically.",\
    "tags": ["modern", "resurrection", "celebration", "testimony"]\
  \},\
  \{\
    "slug": "goodness-of-god",\
    "title": "Goodness Of God",\
    "primary_artist": "Bethel Music",\
    "default_male_key": "A",\
    "default_female_key": "C",\
    "tempo_bpm": 70,\
    "time_signature": "6/8",\
    "themes": ["faithfulness", "gratitude", "trust", "testimony"],\
    "scripture_refs": ["Psalm 23", "Psalm 100:5", "Lamentations 3:22-23"],\
    "summary_theology": "This song reflects on the lifelong faithfulness of God and His steady goodness in every season. It affirms that God is not just good in theory but has walked with us through valleys and joys with patient love. The focus on God pursuing and holding His people anchors the congregation in grace rather than personal effort.",\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This pairs well with testimonies, child dedications, or moments where you want to acknowledge the long story of God with a church. It can be a gentle yet strong closer that lets people express gratitude even if they are still walking through hard things. Encourage worshipers to think of specific memories of God\'92s faithfulness so their singing becomes personal and grounded.",\
    "arrangement_tips": "Keep the intro simple so the first line lands clearly and people can join quickly. Allow the verses to breathe rather than driving them too hard so the weight of the reflection can settle. When the song builds, keep the vocal melody front and center and avoid over layering instruments so the church can carry it.",\
    "tags": ["modern", "faithfulness", "testimony", "slow_build"]\
  \},\
  \{\
    "slug": "living-hope",\
    "title": "Living Hope",\
    "primary_artist": "Phil Wickham",\
    "default_male_key": "C",\
    "default_female_key": "E",\
    "tempo_bpm": 68,\
    "time_signature": "4/4",\
    "themes": ["gospel", "cross", "resurrection", "grace"],\
    "scripture_refs": ["1 Peter 1:3-5", "Colossians 2:13-15", "Romans 5:6-11"],\
    "summary_theology": "This is a gospel rich song that walks through our separation from God, the work of Christ on the cross, and the triumph of the resurrection. It celebrates Jesus as the One who breaks the power of sin and death and opens the way to the Father. The language points clearly to substitution, victory, and the secure hope believers have in Christ alone.",\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "Use this when you want to retell the gospel story in a way that invites both believers and seekers into response. It works well around communion, Easter, or any series focused on the cross and resurrection. Take a moment to frame the song so people are not just singing strong language but actually considering where they stand with Jesus.",\
    "arrangement_tips": "Honor the narrative nature of the verses by not rushing through them and letting the lyrics carry. The chorus can open up dynamically but resist the urge to over compress the bridge so the final lift feels like a joyful proclamation. A short a cappella moment on the last chorus can help anchor the truth in the room.",\
    "tags": ["modern", "gospel_central", "easter", "communion"]\
  \},\
  \{\
    "slug": "great-are-you-lord",\
    "title": "Great Are You Lord",\
    "primary_artist": "All Sons & Daughters",\
    "default_male_key": "D",\
    "default_female_key": "F",\
    "tempo_bpm": 72,\
    "time_signature": "6/8",\
    "themes": ["creation", "breath-of-god", "praise", "dependence"],\
    "scripture_refs": ["Genesis 2:7", "Acts 17:25-28", "Psalm 150"],\
    "summary_theology": "This song focuses on God as the giver of life and breath and the One who deserves all praise. It highlights that our very ability to worship is a gift from Him and that all creation exists to respond to His greatness. The chorus draws a simple but strong line between God\'92s action and our response, keeping the spotlight on His initiative.",\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This works wonderfully as a mid set response where you want the room to lift one clear declaration together. It can also serve near the beginning of a gathering to shift attention off the week and onto the greatness of God. Encourage your team to model honest, unforced worship so the simplicity of the song feels genuine rather than mechanical.",\
    "arrangement_tips": "Let the verses be intimate and spacious with plenty of room for the melody and lyric to breathe. As the chorus repeats, you can introduce gentle harmonies and extra texture but avoid crowding the vocal. The final section can be extended with repeated choruses if the room is engaged but keep the focus on congregational singing, not musical display.",\
    "tags": ["modern", "praise", "call_to_worship", "slow_anthem"]\
  \},\
  \{\
    "slug": "what-a-beautiful-name",\
    "title": "What A Beautiful Name",\
    "primary_artist": "Hillsong Worship",\
    "default_male_key": "D",\
    "default_female_key": "F",\
    "tempo_bpm": 68,\
    "time_signature": "4/4",\
    "themes": ["name-of-jesus", "incarnation", "cross", "victory"],\
    "scripture_refs": ["Philippians 2:9-11", "Colossians 1:15-20", "Hebrews 2:14-15"],\
    "summary_theology": "This song exalts the name of Jesus by reflecting on His divinity, His coming near in the incarnation, and His victory through the cross and resurrection. It holds together beauty, power, and authority in the person of Christ. The song keeps Jesus at the center and invites the church to respond in worship to who He is and what He has done.",\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "Use this when you want to focus a gathering entirely around Jesus and His supremacy. It fits well on Christ centered Sundays, in Christological sermon series, or during moments of ministry where the name of Jesus is being declared over fear or bondage. Invite people to pray quietly or aloud during the softer refrains so the song becomes both praise and intercession.",\
    "arrangement_tips": "The verses do best when sung with clear diction and not too much rhythmic push so the meaning stays accessible. Build the bridge carefully so it feels like a natural swell rather than a sudden jump in volume. Consider ending more quietly rather than always going for the biggest possible ending so the sense of reverence remains.",\
    "tags": ["modern", "christ_exalting", "name_of_jesus", "anthem"]\
  \},\
  \{\
    "slug": "who-you-say-i-am",\
    "title": "Who You Say I Am",\
    "primary_artist": "Hillsong Worship",\
    "default_male_key": "G",\
    "default_female_key": "Bb",\
    "tempo_bpm": 86,\
    "time_signature": "4/4",\
    "themes": ["identity-in-christ", "adoption", "freedom", "grace"],\
    "scripture_refs": ["John 8:36", "Romans 8:14-17", "1 Peter 2:9-10"],\
    "summary_theology": "This song reminds believers that their identity is not defined by shame, performance, or the opinions of others but by what God declares over them in Christ. It emphasizes adoption, freedom, and belonging in the family of God. The language is hope filled and roots identity in the finished work of Jesus rather than in fluctuating feelings.",\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This is a strong choice when your church is wrestling with condemnation, comparison, or insecurity. It can follow a message on identity or grace and works well at youth gatherings where these themes are front and center. Invite worshipers to quietly reject labels that are not from God and receive again what He says about them as they sing.",\
    "arrangement_tips": "Keep the tempo steady and resist over complicating the rhythm so the congregation can fully own the melody. Harmonies in the chorus can add warmth without overshadowing the main line. If you choose to repeat the bridge, consider dropping the band out at least once so the voices alone carry the declaration.",\
    "tags": ["modern", "identity", "freedom", "youth_friendly"]\
  \},\
  \{\
    "slug": "raise-a-hallelujah",\
    "title": "Raise A Hallelujah",\
    "primary_artist": "Bethel Music",\
    "default_male_key": "D",\
    "default_female_key": "F",\
    "tempo_bpm": 82,\
    "time_signature": "4/4",\
    "themes": ["spiritual-battle", "praise-in-trial", "faith", "victory"],\
    "scripture_refs": ["2 Chronicles 20:21-22", "Acts 16:25-26", "Psalm 34:1-3"],\
    "summary_theology": "This song calls believers to worship in the middle of fear, opposition, and unknown outcomes. It frames praise as a weapon that reorients the heart toward God\'92s presence and power rather than the size of a problem. The focus is not on shouting louder to earn a miracle but on responding to the character of God even before circumstances change.",\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "Use this when your community is facing corporate hardship or when you are ministering to individuals walking through deep struggle. It can follow times of intercession for healing or breakthrough and gives a way to respond with faith rather than despair. Encourage people to bring their real emotions to God while still choosing to praise Him.",\
    "arrangement_tips": "Lean into the rhythmic drive and let drums and bass create a strong foundation without overpowering the vocal. Dynamic contrast between verses and choruses keeps the song from feeling like one long wall of sound. Consider a breakdown section that lets the church sing with minimal instrumentation before building again.",\
    "tags": ["modern", "battle", "encouragement", "faith_in_storm"]\
  \},\
  \{\
    "slug": "this-is-amazing-grace",\
    "title": "This Is Amazing Grace",\
    "primary_artist": "Phil Wickham",\
    "default_male_key": "Bb",\
    "default_female_key": "D",\
    "tempo_bpm": 98,\
    "time_signature": "4/4",\
    "themes": ["grace", "cross", "victory", "praise"],\
    "scripture_refs": ["Ephesians 2:4-9", "Colossians 1:13-14", "Revelation 5:11-13"],\
    "summary_theology": "This song celebrates the powerful grace of God shown in Christ who takes our place, breaks the power of sin, and brings us into freedom. It holds together substitutionary language and kingdom imagery that points to Jesus as the worthy King. The tone is joyful and invitational, drawing the church into gratitude for the finished work of the cross.",\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This is a strong opening song that sets a tone of joy and clear gospel focus. It can also work well after a baptism or testimony that highlights freedom from sin. When you lead it, take a moment to frame why the grace of God is truly good news so people do not rush through powerful truths without reflection.",\
    "arrangement_tips": "Keep the groove tight and the melody right in the center of the mix so new people can lock in quickly. Guitars and keys can trade rhythmic roles so the song feels energetic without being cluttered. Do not be afraid to pull the band back on a verse later in the song so the church can hear themselves sing.",\
    "tags": ["modern", "upbeat", "gospel_central", "service_opener"]\
  \},\
\
  \{\
    "slug": "king-of-kings",\
    "title": "King Of Kings",\
    "primary_artist": "Hillsong Worship",\
    "default_male_key": "D",\
    "default_female_key": "F",\
    "tempo_bpm": 68,\
    "time_signature": "4/4",\
    "themes": ["gospel_story", "incarnation", "resurrection", "church"],\
    "scripture_refs": ["John 1:1-14", "Luke 24:1-7", "Acts 2:32-33"],\
    "summary_theology": "This song traces the story of redemption from Christ\'92s coming to His resurrection and the birth of the church. It anchors worshipers in the big narrative of the gospel rather than only in individual experience. The lyrics highlight Jesus as the King whose rule is established through humility, sacrifice, and victory over death.",\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "Use this when you want your church to rehearse the gospel story together in a clear way. It works well in seasons like Advent and Easter or whenever a sermon series follows the life of Christ. Encourage people to engage with the story mentally as well as emotionally so they see how their lives fit into what God has done.",\
    "arrangement_tips": "Treat the verses like chapters in a story and avoid rushing them so the narrative can land. Let the final chorus or tag carry a little more energy to reflect the victorious tone without losing clarity. A simple pad or piano under a spoken scripture before the last section can tie the whole song to a specific text.",\
    "tags": ["modern", "story", "gospel_overview", "seasonal"]\
  \},\
  \{\
    "slug": "ten-thousand-reasons",\
    "title": "10,000 Reasons",\
    "primary_artist": "Matt Redman",\
    "default_male_key": "G",\
    "default_female_key": "Bb",\
    "tempo_bpm": 74,\
    "time_signature": "4/4",\
    "themes": ["gratitude", "faithfulness", "lifelong-worship"],\
    "scripture_refs": ["Psalm 103:1-5", "Psalm 145:1-3"],\
    "summary_theology": "This modern hymn invites believers to bless the Lord in every season and to remember the countless reasons He is worthy of praise. It draws heavily on the psalms and frames worship as a lifelong response, from morning to evening and into eternity. The emphasis is on the goodness and mercy of God which gives courage for both present and future.",\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This is a versatile song that can fit in traditional or modern contexts and across generations. It works beautifully in services of gratitude, memorials, or moments where you want to acknowledge God\'92s care over a long journey. Invite older and younger believers to sing it together so the room feels the intergenerational nature of worship.",\
    "arrangement_tips": "Keep the instrumentation accessible and not overly modern if your church is diverse in style preference. Acoustic guitar or piano can carry the song well with tasteful support from other instruments. Consider having the final chorus gently drop in volume to create a reflective ending rather than always building to the biggest moment.",\
    "tags": ["modern_hymn", "gratitude", "intergenerational", "flexible_style"]\
  \},\
  \{\
