    "title": "Great Things",\
    "primary_artist": "Phil Wickham",\
    "default_male_key": "B",\
    "default_female_key": "D",\
    "tempo_bpm": 126,\
    "time_signature": "4/4",\
    "themes": ["victory", "praise", "redemption", "celebration"],\
    "scripture_refs": ["Psalm 126:3", "Luke 1:49", "Colossians 1:13"],\
    "summary_theology": "This upbeat song praises God for the great things He has done in rescuing His people and defeating the power of darkness. The focus stays on the work of Christ and the freedom believers have through Him. It is a celebration of grace that helps the church respond with joy and confidence in God\'92s ongoing activity.",\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This is a strong first or second song that can wake up a room and direct that energy toward the Lord. It fits well after baptisms or testimonies and can open a series about freedom or redemption. Encourage your team to smile and model joy so it does not feel like a fast song that is sung with serious faces.",\
    "arrangement_tips": "Rhythm section needs to be locked in so the tempo stays steady and does not rush. Keep melodic lines clear, especially in the verses where phrasing can go by quickly. If your congregation is new to it, consider repeating the chorus at the end with simpler instrumentation to let them own it.",\
    "tags": ["modern", "upbeat", "celebration", "service_opener"]\
  \},\
  \{\
    "slug": "glorious-day",\
    "title": "Glorious Day",\
    "primary_artist": "Passion",\
    "default_male_key": "D",\
    "default_female_key": "F",\
    "tempo_bpm": 144,\
    "time_signature": "4/4",\
    "themes": ["salvation", "testimony", "freedom", "resurrection"],\
    "scripture_refs": ["Ephesians 2:4-7", "2 Corinthians 5:17", "Romans 6:4"],\
    "summary_theology": "This song tells the story of moving from death to life because of Christ, celebrating the moment He called us out of the grave of sin and shame. It highlights personal transformation rooted in the finished work of Jesus. The language is testimonial and points to the joy and freedom of a new identity in Christ.",\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "Use this around baptism, testimonies, or youth nights where you want to celebrate salvation in a bold way. It is high energy so pair it with moments where the room is ready to move and sing loudly. Remind people that even if they do not have a dramatic story, they have the same miracle of being brought from death to life.",\
    "arrangement_tips": "Because of the faster tempo, clarity from the drummer and click is crucial so the band stays tight. Keep guitars and keys driving the rhythm together rather than competing. Consider dropping into half time briefly before the last chorus to let the church catch a breath and then explode into the final section.",\
    "tags": ["modern", "testimony", "baptism", "youth_energy"]\
  \},\
  \{\
    "slug": "lord-i-need-you",\
    "title": "Lord I Need You",\
    "primary_artist": "Matt Maher",\
    "default_male_key": "D",\
    "default_female_key": "F",\
    "tempo_bpm": 72,\
    "time_signature": "4/4",\
    "themes": ["dependence", "confession", "grace", "prayer"],\
    "scripture_refs": ["John 15:5", "Psalm 40:1-3", "Hebrews 4:15-16"],\
    "summary_theology": "This song is a prayer of dependence that acknowledges our constant need for the presence and mercy of God. It frames weakness not as failure but as the very place where grace meets us. The theology is simple and pastoral, helping people admit their brokenness and reach for the help of Christ.",\
    "practical_worship_leadership": "This is ideal for confession moments, altar times, or quiet ministry spaces in a service. It can follow a sermon on sin, repentance, or spiritual dryness and gives people language for humility. Invite the room to sit or kneel and sing it as prayer rather than a performance moment.",\
    "arrangement_tips": "Piano or acoustic guitar can carry this effectively with light support from other instruments. Keep the tempo relaxed and resist over embellishing the melody so people feel safe to sing. A softer dynamic overall will help the vulnerability of the lyric land.",\
    "tags": ["modern_hymn", "confession", "ministry_time", "prayer_song"]\
